<asp:Content ID="Content2" runat="server" ContentPlaceHolderID="MainContent">
    <h2 class="header-windows">
        Download and install StateBuilderDotNet
    </h2>
    <h3>
        Requirements</h3>
    <p>
        The <a href="http://download.microsoft.com/download/7/B/6/7B629E05-399A-4A92-B5BC-484C74B5124B/dotNetFx40_Client_setup.exe">
            .NET framework 4.0 client profile</a> is required by StateBuilderDotNet. The
        installer automatically downloads and installs this framework if not already present.
    </p>
    <p>
        In order to build the generated code, one can use <span class="application">Visual Studio</span>
        2008 or 2010, express edition included.</p>
    <h3>
        Download & Install
    </h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Download the setup file <a title="StateBuilderDotNet - State machine code generator for C# and VB.NET"
            href="/Files/StateBuilderDotNet-Setup.exe" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackPageview', '/downloads/StateBuilderDotNet-Setup-Exe'])">
            StateBuilderDotNet-Setup.exe</a> </li>
        <li>Run the setup file <span class="file">StateBuilderDotNet-Setup.exe</span> and follows
            the instructions.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        On the Desktop, a shortcut to the <span class="application">StateBuilderDotNet</span>
        home directory has been created.</p>
    <p>
        A menu entry called <span class="application">StateBuildeDotNet</span> has been
        added.</p>
    <h3>
        Examples</h3>
    <p>
        Have a look at the examples directory <span class="file">Examples\CS</span> or <span
            class="file">Examples\VB</span>. <span class="application">Visual Studio</span> solutions for 2008 and 2010 can be found to build the examples.
    </p>
